{"title_page": "Deoria Tal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}}\n{{coord|30|31|19.9|N|79|7|39.7|E|display=title}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Deoria Tal <br> \u0926\u0947\u0935\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e \u0924\u093e\u0932\n| photo = Deoria_Tal_Chandrashila_Chaukamba_reflection.jpg\n| photo_caption = Reflection of [[Chaukhamba|Chaukhamba Peak]] in Deoria Tal\n| elevation_m = 2438\n| elevation_ref = \n| location = [[Uttarakhand]], [[India]]\n| range = [[Garhwal Himalaya]]\n}}\n\n'''Deoria Tal''' (also '''Devaria' or 'Deoriya''') is a lake about {{convert|3|km|abbr=on}} from the villages of Mastura and Sari on the [[Ukhimath]]-[[Chopta]] road in [[Uttarakhand]]. At an altitude of {{convert|2438|m|sp=us}}, it has heavily wooded, lush green surroundings with snow-covered mountains ([[Chaukhamba]] is one of them) in the backdrop.\n\n==Access==\n[[File:Deoria Taal temple.jpg|thumb|Small temple en route to Deoria Tal]]\nJeeps are available from Ukhimath to reach Sari, a nearby village, via Mastura village. For return journey, one can go down trekking to Mastura to get a shared jeep.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/travellingandtrekkingindia/home/deoria-tal|title=Deoria Tal - Travelling and Trekking|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlternately, one can trek {{convert|7|km|abbr=on}} to Deoria Tal from [[Ukhimath]]. Even though, trekkers are no longer allowed to camp at the famous Deoriatal , there are options of jungle trekking, videography, etc. There are a couple of shops that sell tea and snacks, but these close at sundown. Trekkers usually combine this trek with the nearby trek to [[Tungnath]] (the highest Hindu shrine devoted to Lord Shiva) and [[Chandrashila]], which are approached from Chopta.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chopta.co.in/|title=Chopta travel guide with latest information on chopta trek, Uttrakhand|date=26 December 2013|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Panoramic view===\n<imagemap>\nImage:Himalayan peak Kedarnath ,Chaukhamaba and others from Deoria Tal.jpg|thumb|center|800px|Kedarnath, Chaukhamaba and others Himalayan peak from Deoria Tal. Clicking on a peak in the picture causes the browser to load the existing article about that peak.\n\nrect 1664 385 1375 275[[Chaukhamba]]\nrect 1464 375 1264 280 [[Janhukut]]\nrect 1264 375 1150 280 [[Mandani Peak|Mandani]]\nrect 910 375 875 280 [[Sumeru Peak|Sumeru]]\nrect 834 375 800 280 [[Kharchakund]]\nrect 615 375 565 280 [[Kedar dome]]\nrect 534 375 500 280 [[Kedarnath (mountain)|Kedarnath]]\nrect 434 375 400 280 [[Bhartekunta]]\n</imagemap>\n\nThe lake is known for its wide 300\u00b0 panorama. Mountains like [[Chaukhamba]], [[Nilkantha_(mountain)|Nilkantha]], [[Bandarpunch]], [[Panch Kedar|Kedar Range]], and [[Kalanag]] can be viewed from here. There exists another route from Deoria Tal to Tungnath, which is mainly used for night camping, jungle trekking, etc.\n\n==In the Hindu faith==\nHindu faith states that the [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]] bathed in this lake, hence the name. The lake is also believed to be the \"Indra Sarovar\" referred to in the [[Puranas]] by wandering Hindu mendicants, [[Sadhus]].\nIt is also believed that it was the place where the mighty Pandavas were asked queries by Yaksha. According to the locals, it was also said that this lake was built by Bheem, who was strongest among the Pandavas, to appease his thirst, and Yudhister, who was the wisest, suggested Bheem build his own lake.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mysterioustrip.com/tungnath-chandrashila-deoria-tal-trek/|title=Deoria Tal Kedarnath|publisher=Mysterioustrip|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.budgetyatri.com/2015/03/6-days-of-winter-in-himalayas-solo-2015_49.html|title=6 days of winter in Himalayas - Solo 2015 - Part 5 - Deoria Tal trek - BudgetYatri|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Tungnath-Chandrashila-Deoria-Tal-Trek-pix.jpg|frame|center|Deoria Tal Trek]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hydrography of Uttarakhand}}\n\n[[Category:Lakes of Uttarakhand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}}\n{{coord|30|31|19.9|N|79|7|39.7|E|display=title}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Deoria Tal <br> \u0926\u0947\u0935\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e \u0924\u093e\u0932\n| photo = Deoria_Tal_Chandrashila_Chaukamba_reflection.jpg\n| photo_caption = Reflection of [[Chaukhamba|Chaukhamba Peak]] in Deoria Tal\n| elevation_m = 2438\n| elevation_ref = \n| location = [[Uttarakhand]], [[India]]\n| range = [[Garhwal Himalaya]]\n}}\n\n'''Deoria Tal''' (also '''Devaria' or 'Deoriya''') is a lake about {{convert|3|km|abbr=on}} from the villages of Mastura and Sari on the [[Ukhimath]]-[[Chopta]] road in [[Uttarakhand]]. At an altitude of {{convert|2438|m|sp=us}}, it has heavily wooded, lush green surroundings with snow-covered mountains ([[Chaukhamba]] is one of them) in the backdrop.\n\n==Access==\n[[File:Deoria Taal temple.jpg|thumb|Small temple en route to Deoria Tal]]\nJeeps are available from Ukhimath to reach Sari, a nearby village, via Mastura village. For return journey, one can go down trekking to Mastura to get a shared jeep.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/travellingandtrekkingindia/home/deoria-tal|title=Deoria Tal - Travelling and Trekking|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlternately, one can trek {{convert|7|km|abbr=on}} to Deoria Tal from [[Ukhimath]]. Even though, trekkers are no longer allowed to camp at the famous Deoriatal , there are options of jungle trekking, videography, etc. There are a couple of shops that sell tea and snacks, but these close at sundown. Trekkers usually combine this trek with the nearby trek to [[Tungnath]] (the highest Hindu shrine devoted to Lord Shiva) and [[Chandrashila]], which are approached from Chopta.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chopta.co.in/|title=Chopta travel guide with latest information on chopta trek, Uttrakhand|date=26 December 2013|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Panoramic view===\n<imagemap>\nImage:Himalayan peak Kedarnath ,Chaukhamaba and others from Deoria Tal.jpg|thumb|center|800px|Kedarnath, Chaukhamaba and others Himalayan peak from Deoria Tal. Clicking on a peak in the picture causes the browser to load the existing article about that peak.\n\nrect 1664 385 1375 275[[Chaukhamba]]\nrect 1464 375 1264 280 [[Janhukut]]\nrect 1264 375 1150 280 [[Mandani Peak|Mandani]]\nrect 910 375 875 280 [[Sumeru Peak|Sumeru]]\nrect 834 375 800 280 [[Kharchakund]]\nrect 615 375 565 280 [[Kedar dome]]\nrect 534 375 500 280 [[Kedarnath (mountain)|Kedarnath]]\nrect 434 375 400 280 [[Bhartekunta]]\n</imagemap>\n\nThe lake is known for its wide 300\u00b0 panorama. Mountains like [[Chaukhamba]], [[Nilkantha_(mountain)|Nilkantha]], [[Bandarpunch]], [[Panch Kedar|Kedar Range]], and [[Kalanag]] can be viewed from here. There exists another route from Deoria Tal to Tungnath, which is mainly used for night camping, jungle trekking, etc.\n\n==In the Hindu faith==\nHindu faith states that the [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]] bathed in this lake, hence the name. The lake is also believed to be the \"Indra Sarovar\" referred to in the [[Puranas]] by wandering Hindu mendicants, [[Sadhus]].\nIt is also believed that it was the place from where the mighty Pandavas were asked queries by Yaksha. According to the locals it was also said that this lake was built by Bheem, who was strongest among the Pandavas, to appease his thirst, and Yudhister, who was the wisest, suggested Bheem to build his own lake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelchacha.com/cities/kedarnath/deoria-tal.html|title=Deoria Tal Kedarnath|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.budgetyatri.com/2015/03/6-days-of-winter-in-himalayas-solo-2015_49.html|title=6 days of winter in Himalayas - Solo 2015 - Part 5 - Deoria Tal trek - BudgetYatri|publisher=|accessdate=